    principles: [
      { q: `Look at these pairs from the lessons so far: <span class="pq-ar">يَعْبُدُ</span> vs <span class="pq-ar">عَبَدَ</span>, <span class="pq-ar">يَسْكُنُ</span> vs <span class="pq-ar">سَكَنَ</span>, <span class="pq-ar">يَعْرِفُ</span> vs <span class="pq-ar">عَرَفَ</span>. One of each pair is present tense, the other past. What pattern do you notice in the spelling — not the meaning — that tells them apart?`, a: `Present tense verbs begin with a prefix. Past tense verbs have no prefix, and usually have many fathas ("a" sounds) running through them. This makes it possible to tell them apart even without knowing the meaning.<br><span class="pa-ar">يَعْبُدُ ← عَبَدَ &nbsp;&nbsp; يَسْكُنُ ← سَكَنَ &nbsp;&nbsp; يَعْرِفُ ← عَرَفَ &nbsp;&nbsp; يَقُولُ ← قَالَ &nbsp;&nbsp; يَتْرُكُ ← تَرَكَ</span>` },
      { q: `Look at <span class="pq-ar">أَعْبُدُ</span>، <span class="pq-ar">تَعْبُدُ</span>، <span class="pq-ar">يَعْبُدُ</span>، <span class="pq-ar">نَعْبُدُ</span> — same verb, four different beginnings. What do you think each prefix tells you?`, a: `The present tense has 4 main prefixes: أَـ means "I", يَـ means "he", تَـ means "she" or "you", and نَـ means "we". When the suffix ـونَ is added, the verb becomes plural.<br><span class="pa-ar">أَعْبُدُ (I worship)</span><span class="pa-ar">تَعْبُدُ (she/you worship)</span><span class="pa-ar">يَعْبُدُ (he worships)</span><span class="pa-ar">نَعْبُدُ (we worship)</span><span class="pa-ar">تَعْبُدُونَ / يَعْبُدُونَ (you all / they worship)</span>` }
