    principles: [
      { q: `Look at these sentences from the story: <span class="pq-ar">فَغَضِبَ إِبْرَاهِيمُ وَضَرَبَ الْأَصْنَامَ</span>. Look at the last letter of <span class="pq-ar">إِبْرَاهِيمُ</span> (the one doing the action) and <span class="pq-ar">الْأَصْنَامَ</span> (the one receiving the action). What's different?`, a: `The subject (the one doing the action) takes a damma on its last letter. The object (the one receiving the action) takes a fatha on its last letter. This lets you identify who is doing what, even in a long sentence, without relying on word order.<br><span class="pa-ar">إِبْرَاهِيمُ (subject, damma)</span><span class="pa-ar">الْأَصْنَامَ (object, fatha)</span>` },
      { q: `Look at these verbs: <span class="pq-ar">خَرَجَ</span> ، <span class="pq-ar">خَرَجُوا</span> ، <span class="pq-ar">خَرَجَتْ</span> — same verb, three different endings. What do you think each ending tells you?`, a: `The past tense verb changes depending on who did the action. The base form (no ending) means "he". Add ـوا for a group of men. Add ـتْ for "she" or a feminine noun. For "I" add ـتُ, for "you" add ـتَ, and for "we" add ـنَا.<br><span class="pa-ar">خَرَجَ (he went out)</span><span class="pa-ar">خَرَجُوا (they went out)</span><span class="pa-ar">خَرَجَتْ (she went out)</span><span class="pa-ar">خَرَجْتُ (I went out)</span><span class="pa-ar">خَرَجْتَ (you went out)</span><span class="pa-ar">خَرَجْنَا (we went out)</span>` }
    ]
